        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Gawker industrializes gossip</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Gawker used to be a daring American <strong>gossip and news blog</strong> known for its entertaining and controversial coverage. From celebrities to politicians, no one was off-limits. Founded in 2002 by Nick Denton and Elizabeth Spiers, <strong>Gawker started as a small blog in Denton’s SoHo apartment in New York City</strong>. At its simplest, Gawker was a news and gossip website, but its impact on digital media went far beyond that. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/gawker-media-employee-2009-website-display.png" alt="A Gawker Media employee in 2009 in front of a display of Web sites then operated by the company" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            A Gawker Media employee in 2009 in front of a display of websites then operated by the company. Credits: Redux/Landon Nordeman 
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Over the next 14 years, it became an <a 
          style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-22-02-2025-1-internet-sensation" target="_blank">internet sensation</a>. By 2015, Gawker had over <strong>300 employees</strong> and was drawing in <strong>23 million monthly visits</strong>. It spawned multiple spin-off websites and ignited some of the biggest media controversies. Gawker Media, the parent company, expanded its influence with sites like Gizmodo (tech), Jezebel (women), Kotaku (gaming), Deadspin (sports) and more.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Denton’s vision for Gawker was simple. They produced unfiltered, provocative news that did not pander to traditional media’s objectivity. Its <strong>disregard for privacy</strong> often puts it at odds with the subjects of its stories, leading to <strong>multiple lawsuits</strong>. Critics argued that Gawker disregarded the principles of ethical journalism, choosing sensationalism over responsibility. Others defended its aggressive approach, seeing it as a counterbalance to corporate-controlled media.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

