    <mj-column>
      <mj-spacer height="14px" />
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The lawsuit that killed Gawker</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Gawker’s demise came at the hands of eccentric billionaire Peter Thiel and former wrestler Hulk Hogan. In 2007, <strong>Gawker outed Thiel’s sexuality without his consent</strong>, igniting a long-standing feud. Thiel, co-founder of PayPal and a Republican megadonor, harbored a vendetta against Gawker for years. He quietly funded lawsuits against the company to bring it down.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The final blow came in 2016 when <a 
          style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-22-02-2025-2-gawker-lost-a-lawsuit" target="_blank">Gawker lost a lawsuit</a> over its publication of a leaked salacious tape involving Hulk Hogan. The case raised crucial questions about privacy, freedom of speech, and the responsibilities of digital media. <strong>With Thiel’s financial backing, Hogan won a $140 million judgment against Gawker, forcing the company to file for Chapter 11 bankruptcy</strong>.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Thiel leveraged a mechanism known as <a 
          style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-22-02-2025-3-litigation-financing" target="_blank">litigation financing</a>, or <strong>third-party funding</strong>, where an outside party covers the legal costs of a lawsuit despite having no direct involvement in the dispute. The case is a crucial lesson for any business operating in a high-risk industry. A company must be financially prepared for the inevitable legal battles if it is built on controversy and challenging influential entities.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">How far is too far?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">While Gawker’s style of journalism was often considered trashy, and many <a 
          style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-22-02-2025-4-cheered-its-downfall" target="_blank">cheered its downfall</a>, its demise raised <strong>critical questions about press freedom and corporate resilience</strong>. It exposed the vulnerabilities of independent media in a world where the powerful can dictate the rules and redefine the boundaries of media ethics.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/terry-bolea-hulk-hogan-testifies-gawker-media-trial-st-petersburg-florida.png" alt="Terry Bolea a.k.a Hulk Hogan testifies in court during his trial against Gawker Media, in St Petersburg, Florida" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
           <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            Terry Bolea, a.k.a Hulk Hogan, testifies in court during his trial against Gawker Media in St Petersburg, Florida. Credits: Variety/ Sundance
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">At a time when traditional publications were struggling to adapt to digital disruption, Gawker set the tone for online commentary. <strong>It exposed the mechanics of viral content long before BuzzFeed or Upworthy did and shaped the voice of blogging</strong>. It fueled the industry's evolution even as it critiqued it. For better or worse, it played a pivotal role in redefining how news was consumed, produced, and monetized at the dawn of the digital age.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Despite its controversial reputation, Gawker was undeniably successful and had a strong readership base. <strong>In 2015, just a year before its downfall, it generated $48.7 million in revenue</strong>. Love it or hate it, Gawker left an indelible mark on the media industry, one that continues to spark debate about the lengths of journalism to date.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
